Sierra Nevada

Stretching more than 20 thousand miles, the Sierra Nevada is a mountainous area mainly composed of granitic rocks. Although the climate is mostly mediterranean, some mountains have Boreal and even Alpine climates due to their height, as well as quick temperature changes and strong winds. The region is not particularly rainy, most of the precipitation happens from January to March and the snowpack melts in the Spring.

The Sierra Nevada’s unique climate and geography has led to truly unique ecosystems and wildlife. The mountain range creates a rain shadow, making the east side warmer allowing various pine species and juniper to prosper, while the west has Gray pine, Douglas-fir, and Giant sequoias.

The region is sparsely populated but highly visited for its renowned outdoor recreational activities and iconic landmarks like Lake Tahoe and Yosemite National Park, and Mount Whitney (the largest mountain in the contiguous United States).
